pi estimation using Monte Carlo method

To commemorate pi day this 2024-03-14 I challenged myself to reproduce in R the approach published by Vishal Sharma, where he used Python code to estimate the value of pi.

Original publication

Call libraries

I will use a few popular libraries to calculate the approximation of pi. As a plus I would like to add animation to the plots so I am adding gganimate.

library(ggplot2)
library(tidyr)
library(gganimate)
library(dplyr)

Create table

Next step is to create the table that contains n as the number of iterations, x and y coordinates and a tag that identifies if the point falls within a circle of radius = 1.

n=10000 #number of iterations

df<-data.frame(n=integer(n),
               x_axis=double(n),
               y_axis=double(n),
               tag=character(n),
               approximation=double(n))

df$n<-1:n
df$x_axis<-runif(n)
df$y_axis<-runif(n)
df$tag<-ifelse(((df$x_axis)^2+(df$y_axis)^2>1),"red","blue")

#estimate pi by dividing the number of points that fall within the circle
for (i in 1:n) {
  df$approximation[i]<-4*nrow(df%>%filter(tag=="blue"&n<=i))/i
}

Plot 1

Next is the creation of an animated plot that shows where each random point is located.

options(repr.plot.width=1, repr.plot.height=1) #adjust the plot size

#create the animated plot of a 1/4 circle showing each point from the table
ggplot(df, aes(x=x_axis,y=y_axis,color=tag))+
  geom_point(aes(group=seq_along(n)))+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position="NONE")+
  transition_reveal(n)+
  ease_aes('linear')

#save the animation as a .gif
anim_save("pi_approx_points.gif",path="D:/CVs")

Plot 2

The second plot will show the running estimation of pi in the Y axis and the number of points used for the estimated value in the x axis.

ggplot(df, aes(x=n,y=approximation))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_line()+
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = pi),color="blue")+
  ylim(3.0,3.3)+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position="NONE")+
  transition_reveal(n)+
  ease_aes('linear')

anim_save("pi_approx_line.gif",path="D:/CVs")
